Write a program that does the following

Create an Array - 
num - of the first 5 positive integers
Once the array is defined - output "Done" to the console

code:--

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  int num[] = { 1,2,3,4,5};
  printf("Done");
 
  return 0;
}

Done

############################################################

You have already learned that printf() is used to output (print) values.
Now we will use scanf() to get user input.

scanf() is a predefined variable that reads data from the keyboard or console,

printf(). Used for output
scanf(). Used for input
Write a program that does the following

Declare an integer variable 
a
Try taking a number from the console and assigning it to 
a
Output a to the console


code:--

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  int a;
  scanf("%d", &a);
  printf("Your number is: %d", a);
  return 0;
}

76
##############################################


Write a program that does the following

Declare a string variable x
Accept a text user input - the name of the user - and store it in the variable x
Output and print to the console "Hello" before the user-defined name.
Remember to add a space between "Hello" and x
Note - To read an array of strings we use "%s" format specifier.

code:--

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  char x[10];
  scanf("%s", &x);
  printf("Hello ");
  printf("%s", x);
  return 0;
}

Input
Chef
Output
Hello Chef

###################################################################


We can use the length() function to get the length of a string.
For eg.

char s[] = "hello";
printf("%d", strlen(s)); // a now stores the length of s.
Write a program that does the following

Create a variable 
txt and assign it the text "NumeroTres"
Use the length() function to output to the console the number of characters in 
txt

code:--

#include <stdio.h>
 
int main() {
  char txt[] = "NumeroTres";
  printf("%d", strlen(txt));
  return 0;
}

10
##########################################

Write a program that does the following

Create a string variable 
word and assign the text "Programming" to it
Print the characters 
o and r from the string 
word in separate lines using the syntax defined above

code:
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  char word[] = "Programming";
  printf("%c \n", word[ 2 ]);
  printf("%c", word[4]);
 
  return 0;
}

o
r
#############################################################
Write a program that does the following
Initialise a string variable 
word and assign the value "Ocygen" to it.
You now want to fix the typo in the given string.
Use the syntax explained above to replace 'c' with 'x' in the variable 
word
Output the updated 
word to console

code:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  char word[] = "Ocygen";
  word[ 1 ] = 'x';
  printf("%s", word );

  return 0;
}

Oxygen
